when did we get so scared of bring ourselves that we’ve started preventing others from becoming themselves too? When did labels that were meant to foster connection become tools of exclusion?

as in, “label x means x – only x. the only ppl who can use x are the people who perfectly correspond to the set of rules of x. otherwise, you’re not ‘correctly x.’” 
that’s the opposite of community building. it’s harmful, exclusionary, prevents growth and healthy exploration.

but issues arise when a label is picked because it feels closest to real, and then becomes restrictive and prescriptive – a self-explanatory set of rules that cannot be expanded. 
that’s not good, because it then becomes weaponized as a gatekeeping tool.

that means labels are approximate. in most cases, they’re not perfectly accurate. that doesn’t mean they’re useless, however, just that their use is limited. there are probably not two people for whom a single label means the exact same thing. and that’s fine!
as in, we all only have access to words that are not ours through which we can try to make our (complex, multifaceted) identities intelligible to others and try to find community.
something that’s been on my mind a lot lately: how and when and why did sexual orientation become prescriptive, as opposed to being descriptive?

those are just steps, like haircuts, or a new program, or a new job, or finding THE outfit. 

i think cis people really need to engage with their own gender, otherwise i don’t know that you can even begin to understand what trans people do and who we are. 

the end, i think

so idk that i can say “when” i “started” transitioning. idk if it’s when i came out as a dyke and started low riding my pants, or when i was 4 and hanging out with my brother’s friends, or when i found a trans doctor, or when i did my first shot, or when i bought my first binder.

those are the same self-affirming experiences that everybody can feel, and they feel so good that you just keep trying to experience them again. 

you aren’t a different person bc of that haircut, or that outfit, or that job. you’re just a more accurate version of yourself.

think of haircuts. the way you feel when you walk out of the salon with THE haircut. 

or finding the perfect outfit and feeling the FUCK out of yourself. 

or seeing a job description that you feel was made on measure for you, and you just recognize yourself in the text.
and THAT i not at all a trans-only or transition-only experience. i think most people probably feel that way pretty often, just in ways that are easier to access and much more normalized.

if anything, those are steps that i’ve taken because they felt right, because they’ve allowed me to understand and see myself better, and because they’re just part of becoming a fully fledged version of – gasp – the person i’ve always been.

but the truth is that i’ve never “not” been transitioning, or at least, if there’s a beginning point it’s a decade ago, not a few years ago when i sought out surgeries, not a few months ago when i started testosterone.

and it pinpoints so much of my discomfort with how people *misunderstand* gender as a stable thing rather than a journey. 
I’ve gotten so many “oh so you’re transitioning now?” reactions when i’ve made bigger, externally discernable decisions (top surgery, hormones) –

it doesn’t make sense that stimulants make us calmer, unless you stop thinking about adhd as “hyperactivity.” It’s not a disorder of too-much-energy, it’s a disorder of being unable to figure out how to use that energy in a way that makes sense. 
thanks for coming to my adhd talk

but with meds, suddenly, i can sleep (coffee before bed, anyone?), i can focus on things i like, i can notice my feelings, how they are, how they change, how they affect my thoughts. it’s much easier to be inside my head (and it’s easier to be around me also)

same classroom, same kids, different conditions. 
those kids, in my brain, are thoughts, emotions, reflexions, to-do lists, goals, things i enjoy doing. but without something to help structure, it’s fucking chaos. emotions creeping up unannounced, inability to get my ass in gear

now think of that same classroom with a very alert, very watchful, very awake teacher. much, much less chaotic (hopefully). that’s adhd thoughts with stimulants: it helps the parts of the brain that handle regulation.

think of a second-grade classroom. except the teacher is dead asleep, or just not even there at all. 
fucking pandemonium. chaos everywhere, kids running and screaming because of all the free reign they suddenly have. that’s adhd thoughts
